1
00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:05,600
So in today’s video I’m gonna show you
my go-to smart money strategies, setups I

2
00:00:05,600 --> 00:00:08,769
trade every day for the past 2 years.

3
00:00:08,769 --> 00:00:12,460
This day trading system is designed to be
simple yet effective.

4
00:00:12,460 --> 00:00:18,550
It involves using two time frames, the 30-min
chart and the 5-minute.

5
00:00:18,550 --> 00:00:22,990
Location, context and market structure are
key components.

6
00:00:22,990 --> 00:00:25,490
Here are the step-by-step instructions:

7
00:00:25,490 --> 00:00:26,680
1.

8
00:00:26,680 --> 00:00:29,289
You start by analyzing the 30 min chart.

9
00:00:29,289 --> 00:00:33,380
You look for the direction of the "market
structure" which indicates whether the price

10
00:00:33,380 --> 00:00:36,050
is currently bullish or bearish.

11
00:00:36,050 --> 00:00:41,160
You aim to trade in the same direction as
the order flow, as it provides a general market

12
00:00:41,160 --> 00:00:42,660
bias.

13
00:00:42,660 --> 00:00:47,351
Trending markets are simply markets that are
continuing to break in one direction, either

14
00:00:47,351 --> 00:00:51,440
creating bullish or bearish market structure.

15
00:00:51,440 --> 00:00:57,129
These markets are characterized by two important
moves, the impulsive move, and the retracement

16
00:00:57,129 --> 00:00:58,129
move.

17
00:00:58,129 --> 00:01:03,940
It’s a basic step, but you should be able
to identify these moves almost immediately,

18
00:01:03,940 --> 00:01:08,520
otherwise you will not be able to make the
correct decisions.

19
00:01:08,520 --> 00:01:14,500
An impulsive move is one where the market
moves strongly or heavily in one direction,

20
00:01:14,500 --> 00:01:18,860
covering a great distance in a short period
of time.

21
00:01:18,860 --> 00:01:24,500
Bullish market structure is defined by a market
that is trending up and is creating Higher

22
00:01:24,500 --> 00:01:27,040
Lows (HL), and Higher Highs (HH).

23
00:01:27,040 --> 00:01:32,460
It typically has impulsive up moves and corrective
pull backs.

24
00:01:32,460 --> 00:01:38,140
Bearish market structure is defined by a market
that is trending down and is creating Lower

25
00:01:38,140 --> 00:01:40,490
Highs (LH), and Lower Lows (LL).

26
00:01:40,490 --> 00:01:45,610
It typically has impulsive down moves and
corrective pull backs.

27
00:01:45,610 --> 00:01:50,320
These corrections form against the trend and
they shouldn’t be traded.

28
00:01:50,320 --> 00:01:56,240
You need to know when the corrective moves
ends, and when the impulsive move begins.

29
00:01:56,240 --> 00:02:01,049
Your plan is to anticipate the end of the
corrective moves and the beginning of new

30
00:02:01,049 --> 00:02:02,190
impulsive moves.

31
00:02:02,190 --> 00:02:05,240
By using supply and demand areas.

32
00:02:05,240 --> 00:02:06,240
2.

33
00:02:06,240 --> 00:02:12,750
The next step is to find major supply or demand
areas near the most recent price action.

34
00:02:12,750 --> 00:02:16,819
Or if you’re an ICT student, you look for
order blocks.

35
00:02:16,819 --> 00:02:22,959
So a bullish trend is identified by a series
of movements where the high points exceed

36
00:02:22,959 --> 00:02:24,489
previous highs.

37
00:02:24,489 --> 00:02:30,520
Once identified, your goal will be to find
entry points in Demand zones (when market

38
00:02:30,520 --> 00:02:32,470
is underpriced).

39
00:02:32,470 --> 00:02:39,290
In those zones, buyers add to their positions
and create an imbalance moving the price high.

40
00:02:39,290 --> 00:02:44,930
A bearish trend is confirmed when there are
higher lows and lower lows.

41
00:02:44,930 --> 00:02:51,170
And is characterized by a series of movements
where the low points break the previous lows.

42
00:02:51,170 --> 00:02:57,800
Once determined, your goal will be to find
entry points in lower highs to sell in supply

43
00:02:57,800 --> 00:03:00,319
zones (when market is overpriced).

44
00:03:00,319 --> 00:03:09,680
In those zones, sellers add to their positions
and create an imbalance moving the price lower.

45
00:03:09,680 --> 00:03:16,080
So supply zones represent sellers while demand
zones represent buyers.

46
00:03:16,080 --> 00:03:22,580
In an area of demand there is increased buying
pressure, and the price is expected to rise,

47
00:03:22,580 --> 00:03:27,830
and in an area of supply there is increased
selling pressure, and the price is expected

48
00:03:27,830 --> 00:03:29,330
to decrease.

49
00:03:29,330 --> 00:03:35,630
The idea is to find areas on the chart where
demand overcame supply in an uptrend (for

50
00:03:35,630 --> 00:03:42,760
long trades) or where supply overcame demand
in a downtrend (for short trades).

51
00:03:42,760 --> 00:03:44,989
This is how you draw these zones.

52
00:03:44,989 --> 00:03:50,370
For a supply zone, search the last BULLISH
candle before an important price drop.

53
00:03:50,370 --> 00:03:53,030
And mark the extremes of the candle.

54
00:03:53,030 --> 00:04:00,390
For a demand zone, look for the most recent
candle before an important up move.

55
00:04:00,390 --> 00:04:05,209
As supply and demand traders you will be paying
very close attention to the bigger picture

56
00:04:05,209 --> 00:04:12,370
trend and both the strength of the imbalances
and where in the overall trend these new imbalances

57
00:04:12,370 --> 00:04:13,560
are being created.

58
00:04:13,560 --> 00:04:20,410
There are 2 types of supply and demand zones:
trend continuing zones and reversal zones.

59
00:04:20,410 --> 00:04:25,190
You will mainly look for trend continuing
patterns of supply and demand.

60
00:04:25,190 --> 00:04:27,790
These are formed within the trend.

61
00:04:27,790 --> 00:04:33,560
When the market is moving in an uptrend, price
consolidates for a certain period of time,

62
00:04:33,560 --> 00:04:39,010
forms the the base and then starts to rise
upwards again where it creates an area of

63
00:04:39,010 --> 00:04:40,010
demand.

64
00:04:40,010 --> 00:04:46,320
So, an uptrend requires a Rally followed by
a Base followed by another Rally.

65
00:04:46,320 --> 00:04:54,190
A long position should be entered when the
price comes to mitigate or revisit this area.

66
00:04:54,190 --> 00:05:00,120
In a downtrend, you aim to trade when the
price falls and consolidates, creating a base,

67
00:05:00,120 --> 00:05:04,460
and further breaks down and creates a supply
zone.

68
00:05:04,460 --> 00:05:09,480
A short position is targeted when the price
comes to mitigate this area.

69
00:05:09,480 --> 00:05:16,760
In this continuation pattern, the market doesn’t
retrace much, it pauses and enters in a minor

70
00:05:16,760 --> 00:05:22,400
accumulation or distribution phase before
moving strongly in the same direction.

71
00:05:22,400 --> 00:05:23,460
3.

72
00:05:23,460 --> 00:05:30,010
The third step is wait for the price to retrace
and touch one of your supply or demand zones.

73
00:05:30,010 --> 00:05:34,010
Once the price touches the zone, you move
to the 5-minute chart.

74
00:05:34,010 --> 00:05:36,069
Here’s an important point.

75
00:05:36,069 --> 00:05:40,490
The strength of the impulsive move on the
higher time frame is important when you’re

76
00:05:40,490 --> 00:05:42,030
looking at these imbalances.

77
00:05:42,030 --> 00:05:45,830
It's a key characteristic that can give you
useful information.

78
00:05:45,830 --> 00:05:49,340
But, it's not the only thing you need to consider.

79
00:05:49,340 --> 00:05:56,320
Sometimes, even if you see a very strong imbalance,
where one side (buyers or sellers) is dominating

80
00:05:56,320 --> 00:06:02,320
the market, the market doesn't always react
at the supply or demand zone as you would

81
00:06:02,320 --> 00:06:03,430
expect.

82
00:06:03,430 --> 00:06:08,759
It's like the imbalance is completely ignored
and disappears without any significant impact.

83
00:06:08,759 --> 00:06:14,280
That’s why understanding the context of
the market you're trading in can have a big

84
00:06:14,280 --> 00:06:15,960
impact on your results.

85
00:06:15,960 --> 00:06:22,380
Focus on markets where momentum is strong
and significant price movements, the impulses

86
00:06:22,380 --> 00:06:24,210
we’ve talked before, are occurring.

87
00:06:24,210 --> 00:06:27,310
These markets tend to offer better trading
opportunities.

88
00:06:27,310 --> 00:06:34,720
And, the reason we moved on the lower time
frame was to find other factors of confluence.

89
00:06:34,720 --> 00:06:40,669
When there is confluence, it means that multiple
factors are pointing towards the same conclusion,

90
00:06:40,669 --> 00:06:45,130
reinforcing the significance of that particular
area in the market.

91
00:06:45,130 --> 00:06:51,150
The more technical tools or signals that validate
a price move or confirm the importance of

92
00:06:51,150 --> 00:06:55,490
a specific price level, the stronger that
level becomes.

93
00:06:55,490 --> 00:07:00,509
I mainly use 3 factors of confluence:
• Ultra high volume candle

94
00:07:00,509 --> 00:07:05,539
• Daily vwap rejection
• Change of character

95
00:07:05,539 --> 00:07:13,509
These confluence factors adds a layer of confirmation
and increases the confidence in a trade setup.

96
00:07:13,509 --> 00:07:14,509
4.

97
00:07:14,509 --> 00:07:20,400
Trade only during the London or New York sessions
if you’re trading Forex, indices or crypto.

98
00:07:20,400 --> 00:07:24,789
If you’re trading stocks, you trade of course
during NY session.

99
00:07:24,789 --> 00:07:26,430
This is an important filter.

100
00:07:26,430 --> 00:07:32,530
The London and New York sessions are known
for their high trading volume and liquidity.

101
00:07:32,530 --> 00:07:36,530
Higher liquidity means there are more participants
in the market.

102
00:07:36,530 --> 00:07:42,990
These sessions often experience increased
market volatility compared to other sessions.

103
00:07:42,990 --> 00:07:47,349
Volatility refers to the magnitude of price
fluctuations within a period.

104
00:07:47,349 --> 00:07:53,650
And higher volatility can present more trading
opportunities as prices tend to move more

105
00:07:53,650 --> 00:07:56,240
rapidly, providing potential profit opportunities.

106
00:07:56,240 --> 00:08:00,740
Ultra high volume candle
Let’s talk about the first confluence factor,

107
00:08:00,740 --> 00:08:05,380
which is a high volume candle or an ultra
high volume candle.

108
00:08:05,380 --> 00:08:10,840
I look for pin bars and engulfing bars, to
reveal market rejection.

109
00:08:10,840 --> 00:08:14,490
This is the Yen Futures on the M30 time frame.

110
00:08:14,490 --> 00:08:20,520
As you can see the market was trending down,
making lower lows and lower highs.

111
00:08:20,520 --> 00:08:24,539
As the trend is down, we need to find a supply
zone.

112
00:08:24,539 --> 00:08:30,710
I spot this possible drop-base-drop continuation
pattern, right here.

113
00:08:30,710 --> 00:08:33,779
We move on to the M5 minute time frame.

114
00:08:33,779 --> 00:08:39,810
Market returned to test the zone during the
London session, so this checks another condition.

115
00:08:39,810 --> 00:08:43,820
Now we look for high volume candles, to find
a short entry.

116
00:08:43,820 --> 00:08:50,470
I see this candle with a wick on top of it,
almost a pin bar, having high volume.

117
00:08:50,470 --> 00:08:55,940
This is the VSA condition checked, our factor
of confluence indicating the selling pressure.

118
00:08:55,940 --> 00:08:59,190
Our green light to go short.

119
00:08:59,190 --> 00:09:01,560
Stop loss above the supply zone.

120
00:09:01,560 --> 00:09:05,779
And take profit at the next major demand zones
in the market structure.

121
00:09:05,779 --> 00:09:10,649
I like to take partial profits as the market
moves in my direction.

122
00:09:10,649 --> 00:09:12,990
Same market.

123
00:09:12,990 --> 00:09:16,230
Price made higher high and higher lows.

124
00:09:16,230 --> 00:09:18,769
So we must find a demand zone.

125
00:09:18,769 --> 00:09:24,060
I spot this potential Rally-Base-Rally demand
zone, right here.

126
00:09:24,060 --> 00:09:27,640
Let me quickly explain how these zones are
created.

127
00:09:27,640 --> 00:09:30,120
You need to understand the process.

128
00:09:30,120 --> 00:09:36,130
Before the first rally, we had bank traders
placing trades in the consolidation.

129
00:09:36,130 --> 00:09:40,680
They consume all of the buy orders coming
from retail traders.

130
00:09:40,680 --> 00:09:46,570
The consumption of buy orders means the market
makes a small move lower, this creates the

131
00:09:46,570 --> 00:09:50,720
base, which the demand zones eventually forms
off.

132
00:09:50,720 --> 00:09:56,660
The move lower causes a large number of retail
traders who went long on the rally higher

133
00:09:56,660 --> 00:10:02,640
to close their trades at a loss, which puts
a lot of sell orders into the market.

134
00:10:02,640 --> 00:10:07,600
In addition to this, there will be a small
number of retail traders who think the move

135
00:10:07,600 --> 00:10:13,130
down is a trend reversal, meaning they will
place sell trades with the expectation that

136
00:10:13,130 --> 00:10:15,830
the market is going to move lower.

137
00:10:15,830 --> 00:10:22,029
With two sets of retail traders placing sell
orders, the banks begin buying again knowing

138
00:10:22,029 --> 00:10:27,000
they will make the market move higher, and
in the process cause anybody who sold on the

139
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:33,290
move lower to close their trades at a loss,
which ends up being the bank traders profits.

140
00:10:33,290 --> 00:10:38,279
And during the buying process, the bank may
not find enough sellers and it can’t buy

141
00:10:38,279 --> 00:10:44,410
all the quantities, so it will leave significant
limit orders in the same level, which is a

142
00:10:44,410 --> 00:10:49,830
demand zone, and when the market returns to
test it, prices will be rejected.

143
00:10:49,830 --> 00:10:55,579
Now, let’s go to the M5 time frame, for
the VSA condition.

144
00:10:55,579 --> 00:10:59,510
First, price returned to our zone during the
London session.

145
00:10:59,510 --> 00:11:01,980
I see 2 potential trades.

146
00:11:01,980 --> 00:11:07,280
First one is this pin bar on ultra high volume.

147
00:11:07,280 --> 00:11:13,080
And the second one is this large engulfing
candle on high volume.

148
00:11:13,080 --> 00:11:16,470
Both of these candles were valid buy signals.

149
00:11:16,470 --> 00:11:21,760
With screen time and practice, you will notice
that when the market tests the zone, there

150
00:11:21,760 --> 00:11:26,070
are two possibilities:
Either price goes strongly up, because the

151
00:11:26,070 --> 00:11:30,120
orders left in the zone are enough to push
the market up.

152
00:11:30,120 --> 00:11:36,529
Or the market will still need time to accumulate
enough orders, so we can see a few candles

153
00:11:36,529 --> 00:11:41,399
that form an accumulation phase before the
strong up move.

154
00:11:41,399 --> 00:11:44,149
Stop loss below the demand zone.

155
00:11:44,149 --> 00:11:48,790
And take profit at the next major supply zones
in the market structure.

156
00:11:48,790 --> 00:11:51,579
One more example.

157
00:11:51,579 --> 00:11:54,839
British Pound Futures, M30 time frames.

158
00:11:54,839 --> 00:11:58,519
The price is making lower lows and lower highs.

159
00:11:58,519 --> 00:12:01,300
So we must find a supply zone.

160
00:12:01,300 --> 00:12:03,120
We are in a corrective phase.

161
00:12:03,120 --> 00:12:06,970
The market was trending up, forming a small
rally.

162
00:12:06,970 --> 00:12:13,930
It was followed by a very small consolidation
or a base, and then a very strong move down.

163
00:12:13,930 --> 00:12:19,660
This Rally-Base-Drop supply zone represents
a footprint of financial institutions that

164
00:12:19,660 --> 00:12:22,209
sold the price from that level.

165
00:12:22,209 --> 00:12:26,029
So you follow the footprint and do what the
big boys are doing.

166
00:12:26,029 --> 00:12:30,750
Let’s find the VSA condition on the M5 time
frame.

167
00:12:30,750 --> 00:12:37,310
As you can see the market returned to test
the supply zone, but during the Tokio session.

168
00:12:37,310 --> 00:12:42,540
When you encounter situations like this, it’s
better to wait for the London open, and then

169
00:12:42,540 --> 00:12:44,310
find your entry.

170
00:12:44,310 --> 00:12:49,750
This is important, don’t take trades outside
main market hours.

171
00:12:49,750 --> 00:12:53,870
Prices were initially rejected, but the market
didn’t go down strongly.

172
00:12:53,870 --> 00:12:56,400
Here’s the entry trigger.

173
00:12:56,400 --> 00:12:57,810
Right at the London open.

174
00:12:57,810 --> 00:13:02,380
An engulfing candle with an ultra high volume.

175
00:13:02,380 --> 00:13:08,820
Stop goes above this area, or, if you want
to be conservative, above the supply zone.

176
00:13:08,820 --> 00:14:48,190
Take profit at the next major demand zone,
somewhere around here.

177
00:14:48,190 --> 00:14:53,070
Daily Vwap rejection is another confluence
factor you could look for.

178
00:14:53,070 --> 00:14:58,079
VWAP represents an important price level,
especially in day trading, because it serves

179
00:14:58,079 --> 00:15:00,320
as a reference point or benchmark.

180
00:15:00,320 --> 00:15:06,889
I said it before, when banks execute large
orders, they aim to minimize the impact on

181
00:15:06,889 --> 00:15:12,389
the market by executing the orders gradually
over a period of time.

182
00:15:12,389 --> 00:15:17,029
The VWAP is used as the benchmark price for
this execution period.

183
00:15:17,029 --> 00:15:23,269
To achieve an average price that is equal
to or better than the VWAP, banks place buy

184
00:15:23,269 --> 00:15:26,960
or sell orders based on the price relative
to the VWAP.

185
00:15:26,960 --> 00:15:33,740
On a day when the market is trending upward,
these algorithms will issue buy orders when

186
00:15:33,740 --> 00:15:36,459
the price drops below the VWAP.

187
00:15:36,459 --> 00:15:42,110
This allows them to take advantage of prices
that are below the average, potentially getting

188
00:15:42,110 --> 00:15:44,130
a better deal.

189
00:15:44,130 --> 00:15:50,019
On a day when the market is trending downward,
the same algorithms will issue sell orders

190
00:15:50,019 --> 00:15:52,589
when the price breaks above the VWAP.

191
00:15:52,589 --> 00:15:58,829
This enables them to capitalize on prices
that are above the average, potentially maximizing

192
00:15:58,829 --> 00:16:00,690
their profits.

193
00:16:00,690 --> 00:16:05,730
So how can we, as retail traders, take advantage
of this?

194
00:16:05,730 --> 00:16:12,329
Most retail traders wait for price to cross
the main VWAP line before entering a position.

195
00:16:12,329 --> 00:16:15,800
And that’s a valid strategy, I’ve used
it a lot in my trading.

196
00:16:15,800 --> 00:16:19,370
But the problem is that you are entering very
late.

197
00:16:19,370 --> 00:16:25,690
Often, a big part of the move already took
place and you’re joining the party too late.

198
00:16:25,690 --> 00:16:30,870
That’s why lately, I’ve started taking
trades at the VWAP bands.

199
00:16:30,870 --> 00:16:38,060
VWAP bands are lines above and below the VWAP
projected with multiples of the standard deviation.

200
00:16:38,060 --> 00:16:45,490
I now plot the first and second set of bands,
and I try to take my trades in the area between

201
00:16:45,490 --> 00:16:46,770
them.

202
00:16:46,770 --> 00:16:51,570
Just look at the difference between these
2 potential buy positions.

203
00:16:51,570 --> 00:16:58,120
One at the first VWAP band, and the other
one when price crossed the main VWAP line.

204
00:16:58,120 --> 00:17:00,970
This entry distance is significant.

205
00:17:00,970 --> 00:17:06,299
This can and will make the difference between
a good trade with a proper risk to reward

206
00:17:06,299 --> 00:17:12,470
ratio and one delayed entry, with a poor trade
management.

207
00:17:12,470 --> 00:17:15,069
We are trading EUR Futures.

208
00:17:15,069 --> 00:17:18,650
Price is making lower lows and lower highs.

209
00:17:18,650 --> 00:17:22,600
We are in a downtrend, so we must find supply
areas.

210
00:17:22,600 --> 00:17:26,290
And here is Rally-Base-Drop Supply zone.

211
00:17:26,290 --> 00:17:31,510
Sometimes the base or the consolidation is
not necessarily formed by multiple candles,

212
00:17:31,510 --> 00:17:37,120
as you can see in this example, the market
moved up, formed a pin bar, and then moved

213
00:17:37,120 --> 00:17:38,700
down strongly.

214
00:17:38,700 --> 00:17:44,660
So the base was formed only by one candle,
and this happens frequently in the market.

215
00:17:44,660 --> 00:17:50,059
If you find patterns like these where the
market rallies and drops surprisingly, these

216
00:17:50,059 --> 00:17:54,669
setups are still considered a rally-base-drop
zones.

217
00:17:54,669 --> 00:17:58,929
We move to the lower time frame, to find the
VWAP confluence.

218
00:17:58,929 --> 00:18:03,700
I’ve removed the main VWAP line, and I kept
only the bands.

219
00:18:03,700 --> 00:18:09,190
Look at what happened when the market returned
to test the zone, as you can see, the market

220
00:18:09,190 --> 00:18:12,910
stopped moving up, but before the London session.

221
00:18:12,910 --> 00:18:17,720
We even had a VSA confirmation, with this
engulfing candle on high volume.

222
00:18:17,720 --> 00:18:25,010
Observe how the VWAP bands are offering dynamic
resistance, right at the supply zone.

223
00:18:25,010 --> 00:18:31,190
When this happens, I wait for a pin bar or
an engulfing bar to form in this area.

224
00:18:31,190 --> 00:18:34,080
Stop loss above the supply zone.

225
00:18:34,080 --> 00:18:39,250
And take profit at the next demand zones in
the price structure.

226
00:18:39,250 --> 00:18:40,250
Another trade.

227
00:18:40,250 --> 00:18:42,340
I see an upward trend.

228
00:18:42,340 --> 00:18:44,710
Higher highs and higher lows.

229
00:18:44,710 --> 00:18:50,070
In a strong trending market like this one,
look for a continuation pattern that is composed

230
00:18:50,070 --> 00:18:56,909
of a rally-Base-Rally: a move up followed
by a pause and then another move up.

231
00:18:56,909 --> 00:19:00,260
And here it is: the Demand zone we’ve been
searching for.

232
00:19:00,260 --> 00:19:05,710
The base was not quite a retracement, there
was only a small pause before another move

233
00:19:05,710 --> 00:19:06,710
up.

234
00:19:06,710 --> 00:19:11,990
Now it’s time to find the actual entry point
on the M5 time frame.

235
00:19:11,990 --> 00:19:17,270
First, the retracement happened during the
London session, so we’re good to go if we

236
00:19:17,270 --> 00:19:18,510
find a trigger.

237
00:19:18,510 --> 00:19:24,799
When price retraces to test this zone, we
hope for a rejection, expecting more buy orders

238
00:19:24,799 --> 00:19:26,530
from the banks in this zone.

239
00:19:26,530 --> 00:19:30,020
And look at the power of the VWAP bands.

240
00:19:30,020 --> 00:19:35,190
Price stopped right in the area between the
first and the second VWAP band.

241
00:19:35,190 --> 00:19:38,120
Which also aligns with the demand zone.

242
00:19:38,120 --> 00:19:42,799
The conservative entry is after you find a
pin bar, or an engulfing candle.

243
00:19:42,799 --> 00:19:47,559
But it’s not wrong if you pull the trigger
inside this area.

244
00:19:47,559 --> 00:19:52,840
I’m extra conservative, and I like a candle
confirmation, as an extra confluence.

245
00:19:52,840 --> 00:22:00,659
Stop loss goes below the demand zone, and
take profit and the next supply zones.

246
00:22:00,659 --> 00:22:06,130
Another entry, and maybe the most conservative
and the most delayed one is after a break

247
00:22:06,130 --> 00:22:08,659
of market structure on lower time frames.

248
00:22:08,659 --> 00:22:12,669
A change of character if you are an ICT student.

249
00:22:12,669 --> 00:22:19,660
In simple terms, the first time a lower high
or a higher low is removed from a chart is

250
00:22:19,660 --> 00:22:20,841
known as a CHoCH.

251
00:22:20,841 --> 00:22:28,140
A ChoCh marks an initial shift in order flow
that can sometimes signal a short or even

252
00:22:28,140 --> 00:22:30,720
long-term price reversal.

253
00:22:30,720 --> 00:22:35,760
So this pattern is generally considered a
reversal one, as we’re seeing prices break

254
00:22:35,760 --> 00:22:41,760
internal structure (where a minor level or
supply or demand zone fails).

255
00:22:41,760 --> 00:22:46,559
A change of character should really only be
used as a confluence factor and shouldn’t

256
00:22:46,559 --> 00:22:51,060
be something you rely on solely for getting
market direction.

257
00:22:51,060 --> 00:22:55,320
Use it as a confirmation on the lower time
frames.

258
00:22:55,320 --> 00:22:57,430
We are analyzing EURO Futures.

259
00:22:57,430 --> 00:22:59,090
M30 time frame.

260
00:22:59,090 --> 00:23:03,420
So price is making higher swing highs and
higher swing lows.

261
00:23:03,420 --> 00:23:08,360
The plan is to find a demand zone, and trade
a CHOCH on a lower time frame.

262
00:23:08,360 --> 00:23:11,950
Here’s a bonus tip to find the best demand
zones:

263
00:23:11,950 --> 00:23:19,279
It’s a good sign if you see successive large
bullish candles at the beginning of the supply

264
00:23:19,279 --> 00:23:20,279
zone.

265
00:23:20,279 --> 00:23:24,880
Sometimes the bullish move can come from just
one single large candle.

266
00:23:24,880 --> 00:23:29,840
Other times, there are a few candles appearing
one after another.

267
00:23:29,840 --> 00:23:35,039
But when you see this on your charts, it’s
a clear sign of bullish pressure.

268
00:23:35,039 --> 00:23:38,270
We moved to the lower time frame to find the
change of character.

269
00:23:38,270 --> 00:23:45,490
In this case, we can observe a shift in market
behavior from bearish to bullish on the 5-minute

270
00:23:45,490 --> 00:23:46,720
time frame.

271
00:23:46,720 --> 00:23:52,159
Initially, there was a bearish structure,
but this changed when the last point of supply

272
00:23:52,159 --> 00:23:53,659
failed.

273
00:23:53,659 --> 00:23:59,900
Of course, this CHOCH came as a reaction from
our higher time frame demand zone.

274
00:23:59,900 --> 00:24:04,350
Look at what happened when the market retraced
back to test the demand zone.

275
00:24:04,350 --> 00:24:05,980
A clear rejection.

276
00:24:05,980 --> 00:24:11,600
The concept here is that if price was truly
going to continue in a bearish direction,

277
00:24:11,600 --> 00:24:17,100
it would have respected the last zone of supply
and continued to break through any demand

278
00:24:17,100 --> 00:24:19,460
levels created during the pullback.

279
00:24:19,460 --> 00:24:27,140
However, in this case, the price failed to
do so, indicating a potential shift in momentum.

280
00:24:27,140 --> 00:24:32,820
Another point to consider, the CHOCH happened
outside our trading hours, but very close

281
00:24:32,820 --> 00:24:34,200
to London session.

282
00:24:34,200 --> 00:24:40,350
Again, please don’t rush and try to be patient,
and wait to take your trade during the active

283
00:24:40,350 --> 00:24:41,950
market hours.

284
00:24:41,950 --> 00:24:44,900
You can proceed with your entry in 2 ways.

285
00:24:44,900 --> 00:24:49,290
You can enter right after the CHOCH appears
on the lower time frame.

286
00:24:49,290 --> 00:24:51,260
And this is the risky approach.

287
00:24:51,260 --> 00:24:57,120
There is a risk that price may just be sweeping
the zone before continuing in the same direction

288
00:24:57,120 --> 00:24:59,690
as the previous established trend.

289
00:24:59,690 --> 00:25:05,400
And this presents a danger for those who solely
rely on ChoChs, as they can produce quite

290
00:25:05,400 --> 00:25:07,220
a few false signals.

291
00:25:07,220 --> 00:25:14,390
To increase the accuracy of identifying high-probability
CHOCHs, you might want to use additional confluences.

292
00:25:14,390 --> 00:25:16,080
And this is the second entry method.

293
00:25:16,080 --> 00:25:23,010
You find another lower time frame demand zone,
because you want to buy, and take your trade

294
00:25:23,010 --> 00:25:26,580
from that area if the price returns to it.

295
00:25:26,580 --> 00:25:28,510
This is the conservative entry.

296
00:25:28,510 --> 00:25:34,570
In our case, price indeed retraced to this
5-min demand zone, at the beginning of the

297
00:25:34,570 --> 00:25:36,080
London session.

298
00:25:36,080 --> 00:25:41,929
Keep in mind that if the market has momentum,
you may not get the chance for an entry after

299
00:25:41,929 --> 00:25:43,070
the CHOCH.

300
00:25:43,070 --> 00:25:50,570
Once you’ve identified a good quality supply
or demand zone to trade and in which you’re

301
00:25:50,570 --> 00:25:56,029
expecting a reaction from, you can step down
to the 5-minute timeframe and search for entries

302
00:25:56,029 --> 00:25:58,600
by looking for a change of character.

303
00:25:58,600 --> 00:26:04,190
Keep in mind that sometimes looking for a
ChoCh on the 5-minute may not be enough to

304
00:26:04,190 --> 00:26:06,100
justify placing an entry.

305
00:26:06,100 --> 00:26:11,659
So leave volume indicator on your charts,
or the VWAP, and when things are unclear,

306
00:26:11,659 --> 00:26:15,880
you can consult those tools to make a decision.

307
00:26:15,880 --> 00:26:18,830
We are looking at the futures market of Aussie
dollar.

308
00:26:18,830 --> 00:26:20,350
Obvious uptrend.

309
00:26:20,350 --> 00:26:27,270
A bullish market characterized by rising prices
with many impulsive up moves and smaller corrective

310
00:26:27,270 --> 00:26:28,420
pull backs.

311
00:26:28,420 --> 00:26:35,470
I spot a continuation pattern that forms in
this uptrend, a Rally-Base-Rally demand zone.

312
00:26:35,470 --> 00:26:42,559
This means a move up followed by a short accumulation
phase followed by a move up.

313
00:26:42,559 --> 00:26:46,370
As usual, the plan is to go on the lower time
frame.

314
00:26:46,370 --> 00:26:52,029
When price retraces to test this zone, we
expect to see a rejection, hoping for more

315
00:26:52,029 --> 00:26:54,720
buy orders of other banks in this zone.

316
00:26:54,720 --> 00:27:00,920
In this time frame, we can observe a shift
in price action from bearish to bullish.

317
00:27:00,920 --> 00:27:06,100
Initially, there was a break of structure,
but it turned out to be nothing more than

318
00:27:06,100 --> 00:27:10,440
a liquidity run, taking stops below this zone.

319
00:27:10,440 --> 00:27:15,570
Price broke above the last swing high and
confirmed the change in character.

320
00:27:15,570 --> 00:27:19,390
This is the textbook shift in order flow to
the upside.

321
00:27:19,390 --> 00:27:22,309
One that previously had a liquidity run.

322
00:27:22,309 --> 00:27:27,570
The demand rejection happened during Tokio
session, and the CHOCH happened right at the

323
00:27:27,570 --> 00:27:30,140
beginning of the London session.

324
00:27:30,140 --> 00:27:33,990
This is another sign than you are trading
on the correct side of the market.

325
00:27:33,990 --> 00:27:40,210
It’s always nice to see immediate volatility
and market reaction when you’re entering.

326
00:27:40,210 --> 00:27:43,779
Again, you can proceed with your entry in
2 ways.

327
00:27:43,779 --> 00:27:48,290
The risky approach: right after the CHOCH
appears on the lower time frame.

328
00:27:48,290 --> 00:27:53,880
With the risk that price may just be sweeping
the zone before continuing in the downward

329
00:27:53,880 --> 00:27:55,220
direction.

330
00:27:55,220 --> 00:28:00,899
Or you wait for price to retrace to a recent
demand zone, formed prior to the change of

331
00:28:00,899 --> 00:28:01,960
character.

332
00:28:01,960 --> 00:28:03,539
The conservative entry.

333
00:28:03,539 --> 00:28:07,710
In this particular example, the retracement
never came.

334
00:28:07,710 --> 00:28:12,630
Market had momentum at the beginning of the
session, and of you didn’t enter after the

335
00:28:12,630 --> 00:29:52,810
CHOCH, you didn’t get the second chance
for an entry.

